Title:
Using CLR Hosting to Evade AMSI

Type:
Technical Paper

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This paper analyzes how AMSI scans .NET assemblies and presents an evasion technique that avoids common in-memory patching approaches.  
- It reverse engineers .NET Framework assembly-loading paths in `clr.dll` and identifies that some loaders (notably `StreamImageLayout`) do not trigger AMSI scanning, unlike `RawImageLayout` used by typical `AppDomain.Load(byte[])`/buffer-based loads.  
- The author demonstrates using Microsoft-documented CLR Hosting APIs from a native (C/C++) host to influence assembly resolution/loading so the CLR consumes an `IStream` (memory-backed) and bypasses AMSI inspection.  
- The technique relies on implementing COM hosting interfaces (`IHostControl`, `IHostAssemblyManager`, `IHostAssemblyStore`) to supply the assembly image via `IStream` (e.g., `SHCreateMemStream`) when the CLR fails to resolve it normally (e.g., not found in GAC).  
- A practical example shows executing a known offensive .NET tool (Rubeus) without obfuscation and without AMSI blocking, contrasting with AMSI-blocked behavior when loading via direct memory buffer methods.  
- Useful for red teams and malware/tool developers; also valuable to defenders for understanding blind spots in AMSI coverage and where to instrument detections beyond classic AMSI patch signatures.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI internals and call flow (`AmsiInitialize`, `AmsiOpenSession`, `AmsiScanBuffer`)
- .NET Framework assembly loading internals (`clr.dll`, `AssemblyNative`, `PEImageLayout` subclasses)
- CLR Hosting APIs and COM interfaces (`ICLRMetaHost`, `ICLRRuntimeInfo`, `ICLRRuntimeHost`, `ICorRuntimeHost`)
- Custom assembly resolution via hosting (`IHostControl`, `IHostAssemblyManager`, `IHostAssemblyStore`)
- `IStream`-based loading (`StreamImageLayout`, `SHCreateMemStream`) vs buffer-based loading (`RawImageLayout`)
- Strong-name assembly binding and GAC resolution behavior

Use Cases:
- Build a native CLR host to execute managed payloads while avoiding AMSI’s .NET assembly scan path
- Execute/reflectively invoke .NET post-exploitation tooling (e.g., Rubeus-like assemblies) without classic AMSI patching
- Research/detect alternative .NET loading paths that bypass AMSI and design compensating telemetry (ETW/CLR load events)
- Develop PoCs to validate AMSI coverage gaps across .NET Framework versions and loader variants

Keywords:
AMSI, AmsiScanBuffer, amsi.dll, MpOav.dll, .NET Framework, CLR, clr.dll, mscoree.dll, CLR Hosting, ICLRMetaHost, ICLRRuntimeInfo, ICLRRuntimeHost, ICorRuntimeHost, IHostControl, IHostAssemblyManager, IHostAssemblyStore, AppDomain, AssemblyNative, PEImageLayout, StreamImageLayout, RawImageLayout, IStream, SHCreateMemStream, strong name, GAC, reflection, dnSpy, IDA, ETW